<div class='communityQuestion'>
<div class='questionText'>
<a href="/questions/452906-is-this-book-a-religous-one">Is this book a religous one???</a>
</div>
<div class='communityQAFooter questionFooter'>
<ul class='questionFooterActions'>
<li class='footerItem like'>
<span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_community_question_452906'><a id="like_count_community_question_452906" rel="nofollow" href="/rating/voters/452906?resource_type=CommunityQuestion"><span class="likesCount">8 likes</span></a>&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;<a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F29641.The_End_of_the_Affair">like</a></span>

</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionTimestamp'>
<a href="/questions/452906-is-this-book-a-religous-one">6 years ago</a>
</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionPermalink'>
<a href="/questions/452906-is-this-book-a-religous-one">See all 6 answers</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/12882225-nicholas"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1355429284i/12882225._UX100_CR0,33,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/12882225-nicholas">Nicholas</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">This book has religious and philosophical themes in the way that The Brothers Karamazov does, but it is not religious apology. Rather, it a literary e<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">This book has religious and philosophical themes in the way that The Brothers Karamazov does, but it is not religious apology. Rather, it a literary exploration of religion and its role (or lack thereof) in human life/love/grief. The book contains arguments both for and against the existence of (G)od without attempting to persuade the reader of either position. Throughout the book, some of the characters struggle with belief/disbelief. From a philosophical and literary standpoint, it is one of the most interesting treatments that I have read on the subject. Beautiful book. I would highly recommend it.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
